                      <span>15</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-02-27</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>In the film "Intimacy", every Wednesday afternoon, between the hours of 2 and 4, Jay (Mark Rylance) and Claire (Kerry Fox) meet for sex. These almost wordless encounters occur on the grubby floor of Jay's squalid home. There's grunting, groaning, and groping galore as the pair couple in many frantic, loveless clinches. 
<br />
<br />Apparently, this arrangement started rather casually, and now it's become a regular habit. Jay, a head barman at a London club, is an unlikable character. He's a failed musician, and according to the story he tells fellow employees, he packed a bag one day and left his wife and two children. It's hard to know what motivates this man. In his disgustingly filthy home, he hasn't even bothered to unpack boxes. One day, after the conclusion of yet another Wednesday afternoon tryst, he follows Claire and discovers her real life. 
<br />
<br />The sex depicted in the film is just about the most graphic I've seen this side of a "adult" film. However, that said, the sex scenes are not glossy or glamorous or enhanced by any drippy musical scores--they're just boring. Also, I kept thinking how uncomfortable and impractical the situation would be amidst all the debris, filth, and crumbs. Doesn't this man even have a mattress? The most interesting parts of the film occur when Jay discovers Claire's life and family. Just what is Jay's game? As Jay intrudes into Claire's private life, it becomes obvious why they both need to compartmentalize once-a-week encounters. As a fellow employee tells Jay "it's not very often you come across someone who wants the same thing." The film is based on short stories by Hanif Kureishi, and this explains the film's bitter cynical edge (and why I wanted to watch it in the first place). With great performances, and dark moody sets, keep your eyes open for the character of Betty played by Marianne Faithfull--displacedhuman </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">I love you on wednesday, but not on thursday-E.S.V.Millay</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
